P1 – Binary Search Tree Construction and Traversals

Course:
Program Translation / Compilers

Author:
Jory Ehman


OVERVIEW

This program constructs a Binary Search Tree (BST) using the ASCII
value of the first character of each input string as the key.

Each node contains:
- An integer key (ASCII value)
- Left and right child pointers
- A vector of strings sharing the same key

The program:
1. Reads input from standard input or a file.
2. Validates characters according to project rules.
3. Builds the BST while maintaining ordering invariants.
4. Produces three traversal outputs:
   - Pre-order
   - Post-order
   - Level-order
5. Frees all dynamically allocated memory before exiting.


------------------------------------------------------------
COMPILATION
------------------------------------------------------------

To compile the program:

    make

This creates the executable:

    P1


------------------------------------------------------------
CLEANING THE PROJECT
------------------------------------------------------------

To remove:
- Object files (*.o)
- Executable (P1)
- Generated traversal output files (*.preorder, *.postorder, *.levelorder)

Run:

    make clean


------------------------------------------------------------
RUNNING THE PROGRAM
------------------------------------------------------------

1) Running Without an Input File (Keyboard Mode)

    ./P1

You may now type input directly, for example:

    M C T A E R Z

When finished entering input, press:

    CTRL + D

This will generate:

    out.preorder
    out.postorder
    out.levelorder


------------------------------------------------------------

2) Running With an Input File

General usage:

    ./P1 filename.txt

Example:

    ./P1 test1.txt

This generates:

    test1.preorder
    test1.postorder
    test1.levelorder

Note:
The .txt extension is removed before traversal suffixes are added.


------------------------------------------------------------
INCLUDED TEST FILES
------------------------------------------------------------

test1.txt – Balanced Tree

Contents:
    M C T A E R Z

Run:
    ./P1 test1.txt

Verifies:
- Balanced BST construction
- Correct indentation (4 spaces per depth)
- Proper preorder, postorder, and levelorder outputs


------------------------------------------------------------

test2.txt – Multiple Strings Same ASCII Key

Contents:
    apple ant a1 alpha

Run:
    ./P1 test2.txt

Verifies:
- Only one node created (ASCII 97)
- All strings stored in same vector
- Single-line traversal output


------------------------------------------------------------

test3.txt – Case Sensitivity (ASCII Ordering)

Contents:
    Apple ant A1

Run:
    ./P1 test3.txt

Verifies:
- ASCII 65 ('A') vs ASCII 97 ('a')
- Proper left/right placement


------------------------------------------------------------

test4.txt – Deep Unbalanced Tree

Contents:
    A B C D E F G

Run:
    ./P1 test4.txt

Verifies:
- Right-skewed tree structure
- Proper recursion depth handling
- Correct indentation scaling


------------------------------------------------------------

test5.txt – Invalid Character Detection

Contents:
    valid1 invalid~

Run:
    ./P1 test5.txt

Expected output:
    Error: Invalid character encountered

No traversal files should be created.


------------------------------------------------------------

test6.txt – Empty File

(Empty file)

Run:
    ./P1 test6.txt

Expected output:
    Error: Missing data

No traversal files should be created.


------------------------------------------------------------
IMPROPER USAGE
------------------------------------------------------------

If more than one filename is provided:

    ./P1 file1.txt file2.txt

Output:

    Fatal: Improper usage
    Usage: P1 [filename]


------------------------------------------------------------
TREE INVARIANT
------------------------------------------------------------

The BST maintains:

- Left subtree keys < current node key
- Right subtree keys > current node key
- Equal keys stored in the same node


------------------------------------------------------------
TRAVERSAL OUTPUT FORMAT
------------------------------------------------------------

Each output line follows:

    <depth> <ascii_key> <strings>

Indented by 4 spaces per depth level.

Traversal types implemented:

- Pre-order (Node → Left → Right)
- Post-order (Left → Right → Node)
- Level-order (Breadth-first using queue)


------------------------------------------------------------
MEMORY MANAGEMENT
------------------------------------------------------------

All nodes are dynamically allocated using new.

Memory is freed using post-order deletion:

    deleteTree(node_t* root);

This ensures no memory leaks.


------------------------------------------------------------
TARGET ENVIRONMENT
------------------------------------------------------------

Platform: hellbender
Compiler: g++
Standard: C++11
No use of "using namespace std"
Modular procedural design
No global variables